node.text:
Explosive scoring guard Mikey Williams — @mikey — of San Diego, Calif., won’t be eligible for the NBA Draft until 2024. He still has nearly two years to decide on college basketball or a pro pathway. Yet his massive social media empire -- over 5 million followers across several platforms – has allowed him to become the first prep basketball star to sign with a major sports representation agency to pursue NIL endorsements and sponsorships. 
Williams, who’ll attend Lake Norman in Charlotte and plans to play basketball for the Vertical Academy, has signed a deal with @excelsm that Excel Vice-President Matt Davis believes “will generate millions of dollars for this young man.” 
	“Mikey’s relevance around his peers in the basketball community is off the charts,” Davis told ESPN. “He’s one of the most relevant personalities in the basketball community. His digital and social following speak for themselves.” 
In a statement, Williams told ESPN: “

"The NIL rules provide a new opportunity for someone like me who that has put in so much energy and effort into building a community. I am excited to be the first high school athlete to make this move. I love to hoop and I love engaging with my fans and look forward to continuing to share my journey with everyone."

node.text:
ESPN Sources: Denver Nuggets G/F Will Barton has declined his $14.7M player option for the 2021-2022 season and will become a free agent. There’s a strong interest between the organization and Barton to negotiate a new deal once free agency opens in August.

The longest tenured Nugget with 7 seasons, Barton is a top priority for Tim Connelly to keep long-term. Barton started 52 games and averaged 12.7 PPG this year. He lost several weeks with a hamstring injury into the start of playoffs, but finished with a 25-point performance vs. Suns in elimination game.

node.text:
Wes Unseld Jr., has agreed to a four-year deal to become the new head coach of the Washington Wizards, sources tell ESPN.

The Wizards offered the job to Denver's associate head coach on Friday, and worked out terms today with his agent @elfussports to complete a formal agreement, sources said.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Adrian Wojnarowski on July 16, 2021. May be an image of 1 person.

node.text:
The Washington Wizards are offering Denver Nuggets assistant Wes Unseld, Jr., the franchise’s head coaching job and sides are beginning contract talks on Saturday with an expectation of a deal this weekend, sources tell ESPN.

A deal will tie together a remarkable homecoming: Unseld’s late father, Wes Unseld, is the most important figure in franchise history -- a Hall of Fame player, coach and executive with Washington.
Contract talks are expected to begin on Saturday.
